The start of the 2022 National Sevens Circuit has been pushed back by two weeks and will now kick off on May 21 and not May8-9 as earlier announced. Kenya Rugby Union have announced a revised schedule which has seen the competition pushed backward by two weeks. The campaign will kick off with Mwamba Rugby Club hosting the George Mwangi Kabeberi Sevens on May 21-22 at a venue that will be confirmed later. Thereafter the teams will then head to the RFUEA ground for the Christie 7s on May 28-29. The teams will take a week's break before heading to the Bull's Ring for Kakamega 7s on  June 11/12. Seven days later, the clubs will make the trip to the coastal town for the Driftwood 7s scheduled for Mombasa Sports Club. A one week break will follow before the teams conclude the campaign with Dala 7s at Jomo Kenyatta Stadium and Prinsloo in Nakuru on subsequent weekends The circuit returns following a two-year hiatus caused by the the Covid-19 -pandemic and will give Kenya Sevens head coach Innocent Simiyu a chance to assess new talent in the country to play for the national team. KCB Rugby are the defending champions having won the Inaugural Kakamega 7s, Dala 7s, Christie 7s and Driftwood 7s. Elsewhere,' the promotion battle in the second-tier KRU Championship remains finely poised heading into the final round of action in the league phase of the competition. South Coast Pirates, Shamas, Mean Machine, Catholic Monks and Western Monks are all in with a chance of making the semifinal. South Coast Pirates’ 28-0 result over Eldoret take them to the top of the log with 38 points from 10 outings. They are two points clear of second-placed Shamas who are on 36 points after subjecting relegation threatened Northern Suburbs to a 30-6 defeat. Mean Machine sit third on 35 points after falling to a 17-15 home defeat to Western Bulls.